The temperature variation of the PV cell with natural air cooling is illustrated in Figure S7a. The air around the cell is heated, which leads to natural convection induced by the density difference of air. The effective heat transfer coefficient of natural air cooling is 1.04 W/m2·K, which is very low, and the temperature consistently rises because of the constantly supplied heat (in general, the heat transfer coefficient of natural air cooling is less than 10 W/m2·K). The natural convection of air can be characterized by the Rayleigh number in Eq. (6). Δρ is the density difference owing to temperature variation (kg/m3), l is the characteristic length of the cell (m), g is the gravitational acceleration (m/s2), μ is the dynamic viscosity of air (Pa·s), and α is the thermal diffusivity (the ratio of thermal conduction to absorbed heat; m2/s).6Ra=Δρ⋅l3⋅gμ⋅α\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
